Storefront Proxy — Solution Summary
=====================================

## What exists today

There's already a dispatcher/proxy system that routes admin requests to OrderCloud. It works by taking a Sitecore Identity token (an employee badge), checking what tenant/environment the user belongs to, and forwarding the request to the right OrderCloud region. The token itself doubles as the authorization — OrderCloud accepts it directly.

This system intentionally blocks auth endpoints (login, registration) because admins authenticate through Sitecore Identity, not through OrderCloud directly.


## What's needed

SitecoreAI sites need to let shoppers (anonymous visitors and registered buyers) interact with OrderCloud — login, browse products, manage carts, place orders. These shoppers don't have a Sitecore Identity token. All they have is a Context ID, which is a public identifier already used by Sitecore rendering hosts.

So the system needs a second path through the proxy that:
- Works with a Context ID instead of an admin token
- Enables auth endpoints (so buyers can log in and register)
- Restricts access to only buyer-safe endpoints (no admin operations)
- Figures out the right OrderCloud tenant and Client ID automatically from the Context ID alone


## How it works, end to end

Step 1 — New routes in the dispatcher.
The dispatcher (traffic cop) gets new URL patterns: /storefront/* and /v1/storefront/*. These are separate from the existing /oc/* admin routes. When a request hits one of these, the dispatcher knows it's a shopper request and handles it differently.

Step 2 — Context ID is required.
Unlike the admin proxy (which can work without context), the storefront proxy demands a Context ID on every request. The dispatcher uses it to look up an "ordercloud" resource, which contains a tenant_id. No Context ID, no entry.

Step 3 — Hand off to a new worker.
The dispatcher forwards the request (with tenant info attached) to a brand-new Cloudflare Worker called sitecore.ep.proxy.storefront. This is a separate service from the existing admin proxy, so they deploy and evolve independently.

Step 4 — The new worker looks up the full config.
The storefront proxy takes the tenant_id and calls the Inventory API (an internal service that already knows about all OrderCloud tenants). The Inventory API returns everything needed: the OrderCloud base URL, marketplace ID, region, and — crucially — a SitecoreAI.ClientId (the buyer-facing API Client ID).

Step 5 — Endpoint allowlist.
The proxy only permits buyer-safe paths:
- /v1/oauth/* — login, registration, anonymous tokens
- /v1/me/* — buyer profile, product browsing, cart, orders

Everything else (admin endpoints, user management, catalog management) is blocked.

Step 6 — Client ID injection.
For OAuth requests (login, anonymous token), if the shopper's request doesn't include a client_id, the proxy injects the SitecoreAI.ClientId it got from the Inventory API. This means a storefront can authenticate with just a Context ID — it never needs to know or expose the OrderCloud Client ID.

Step 7 — Token handling for everything else.
For non-auth requests, the shopper must provide their own OrderCloud access token (obtained in step 6). The proxy does a lightweight format check on the JWT but does not verify the signature — it lets OrderCloud be the final authority.

Step 8 — Forward to OrderCloud.
The proxy strips the /storefront/ prefix, builds the real OrderCloud URL, attaches the token, and sends the request through. The response comes back to the shopper.


## How the Client ID gets there in the first place (Provisioning)

Explicit provisioning (not dynamic discovery):
- When a new SitecoreAI tenant is set up, the provisioning system creates a dedicated OrderCloud API Client configured for buyer use (anonymous access enabled, all buyers allowed).
- The provisioning system writes that Client ID into the Inventory API as a SitecoreAI.ClientId annotation on the tenant record.
- The Context Service gets a new "ordercloud" resource type that stores the tenant_id.
- At runtime, the proxy just reads what's already there — no admin credentials needed, no API client listing, no auto-creation.


## Error Handling

These are defensive guards for when setup/config is wrong — not errors shoppers should ever see on a correctly-provisioned tenant.

No Context ID on request:
- Why: Frontend didn't attach the Context ID header. Misconfigured site, direct API call, or a bot.
- Who: Frontend integration bug.

Context has no "ordercloud" resource:
- Why: The Context ID exists (set up for personalize, forms, etc.) but nobody added the ordercloud resource. OC wasn't wired in yet.
- Who: Incomplete site setup.

Tenant not found in Inventory API:
- Why: The tenant_id points to a tenant that no longer exists — decommissioned, environment mismatch, or typo.
- Who: Stale or wrong config.

No SitecoreAI.ClientId annotation:
- Why: Legacy tenant that predates this feature and hasn't been migrated, or provisioning partially failed (OC client created but annotation write-back didn't complete).
- Who: Migration gap or partial provisioning failure.

OrderCloud rejects the Client ID:
- Why: Someone deleted/deactivated the API Client directly in OrderCloud without updating the Inventory API annotation.
- Who: Out-of-band change in OrderCloud.

Bottom line: For a fully-provisioned, correctly-configured tenant, shoppers hit zero errors. These guards give ops/platform teams clear, actionable messages when setup is wrong.


## Deferred to later iterations

- Auto-obtaining anonymous tokens — the browser manages its own token lifecycle
- Rate limiting — start with OrderCloud's built-in limits, add Cloudflare limiting later if needed
- Response caching — passthrough only for now
- Multi-storefront per marketplace — one Client ID per marketplace initially; revisit if distinct buyer pools are needed
